                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d504">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">561.311D1/62: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-05-26T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 26, 1931—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>147. For Olsen from the Department of Agriculture. Cable your personal opinion
                    fundamental value wheat clearing house and permanent participation of this
                    Government. What evidence is there that clearing house will obtain data not
                    obtainable by our foreign services and International Institute of Agriculture?
                    Is there assurance Russia will furnish clearing house information not otherwise
                    available? Will clearing house be able induce participating Governments to
                    improve their official wheat statistics beyond improvements obtainable without
                    creating a new agency?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
